Appendix B: Background on von Neumann Algebras and Modular Theory

This appendix provides a more detailed exposition of the operator algebraic concepts used in the thesis.

B.1 C*-Algebras and von Neumann Algebras

Definition B.1. A C*-algebra $\mathcal{A}$ is a Banach $*$-algebra satisfying $\|a^*a\| = \|a\|^2$ for all $a$.

Definition B.2. A von Neumann algebra $\mathcal{M}$ is a C*-algebra that is closed in the weak operator topology (or equivalently $\mathcal{M} = \mathcal{M}''$) when represented on a Hilbert space.

Examples. $B(H)$, $L^\infty(X,\mu)$ acting on $L^2(X,\mu)$, group von Neumann algebras $VN(G)$.

B.2 States and Representations

Definition B.3. A state $\omega$ on $\mathcal{A}$ is a positive linear functional of norm 1.

GNS Construction: Given $\omega$, there exists a Hilbert space $H_\omega$, a representation $\pi_\omega: \mathcal{A} \to B(H_\omega)$, and a cyclic vector $\xi_\omega$ such that $\omega(a) = \langle \xi_\omega, \pi_\omega(a)\xi_\omega\rangle$.

B.3 Modular Theory (Tomita-Takesaki)

Let $\mathcal{M}$ be a von Neumann algebra with a cyclic and separating vector $\Omega$ (e.g., from a faithful state). Define the antilinear operator $S: a\Omega \mapsto a^*\Omega$ (initially defined). Its closure has polar decomposition $S = J \Delta^{1/2}$, where $J$ is an antilinear involution (modular conjugation) and $\Delta = S^*S$ is the modular operator. Then:

· $\Delta^{it} \mathcal{M} \Delta^{-it} = \mathcal{M}$ for all $t$ (modular automorphism group).
· $J \mathcal{M} J = \mathcal{M}'$ (commutant).

KMS Condition: For $\omega$ faithful, $\omega(x \sigma_t^\omega(y)) = \omega(y \sigma_{t+i}^\omega(x))$ for analytic elements, encoding the "time" flow.

B.4 Types of von Neumann Algebras

· Type I: Contains minimal projections (matrix algebras, $B(H)$).
· Type II: Has a trace but no minimal projections (e.g., hyperfinite $II_1$ factor).
· Type III: No trace, modular automorphism group non-trivial, occurs in QFT.

B.5 Conditional Expectations

Definition B.4. For $\mathcal{N} \subseteq \mathcal{M}$, a conditional expectation $\mathbb{E}: \mathcal{M} \to \mathcal{N}$ is a UCP map satisfying $\mathbb{E}(x y z) = x \mathbb{E}(y) z$ for $x,z \in \mathcal{N}$.

Theorem (Tomiyama). Such a map is necessarily a contraction. Existence is linked to modular invariance.

