Appendix F: Tensor Network Representations for Non-Commutative Inference Models

F.1 Matrix Product States (MPS)

For a 1D chain of $N$ sites with local dimension $d$, an MPS is $|\psi\rangle = \sum_{s_1,\dots,s_N} \operatorname{Tr}(A_1^{s_1} \cdots A_N^{s_N}) |s_1\cdots s_N\rangle$. The bond dimension $D$ controls entanglement.

F.2 Representing States on C*-Algebras

If $\mathcal{A} = \bigotimes_{i=1}^N M_d(\mathbb{C})$, a state can be represented by an MPS of the form $\rho = \operatorname{Tr}_{\text{anc}}(|\Psi\rangle\langle\Psi|)$ where $|\Psi\rangle$ is an MPS on an enlarged space.

F.3 Bayesian Update with Tensor Networks

Given a prior MPS $\rho$ and a likelihood channel $\Phi$ (which may be local), the Petz map $\mathcal{P}_{\omega,\Phi}$ can be implemented using tensor network techniques such as TEBD or DMRG, enabling efficient approximate Bayesian inference.

F.4 Complexity

MPS representations allow efficient computation of expectation values, relative entropies, and gradient flows, provided the bond dimension remains manageable. This connects the abstract theory to practical algorithms.

